Geospatial Data Analytics with Python¶

Introduction¶

This project will use Python to build a machine learning pipeline to predict the class label on how much Calgarians spend on automobile purchases. The study area will be Calgary, Alberta containing over 1700 dissemination areas. As mentioned, the target variable will be automobile purchase range. The predictor variables are:

  • median age
  • median household income
  • average food spend
  • average shelter spend
  • marital status
  • health care spend
  • education (bachelor or above)

Data Importing¶

The data used in this notebook is a sample of Dissemination Area data from the Business Analyst Canada 2023 dataset, provided by Esri Canada. It is for educational and demonstration purposes only, and should not be shared without permission.

The data comprises a small sample of Dissemination Areas roughly corresponding to the City of Calgary. The data was initially exported from ArcGIS Pro as a Shapefile. It has been enriched with several generic demographic and spending variables, intended to serve as predictors in our model building exercise.

As a spatial data set, we will use the GeoPandas package to import it into our notebook.

Trimming the Outliers¶

There are many ways to determine if a value represents an outlier. One way is to use standard deviations, setting a specific threshold value beyond which values are considered outliers. For example, in this demonstration, we will use the threshold value of 3 standard deviations. That means, if a given DA has a Automobile_Avg value that is greater than or less than 3 standard deviations from the mean Automobile_Avg value, it will be considered an outlier and will be trimmed from the dataset.

A simple way to implement this approach is to convert the given numeric variable to a scaled version of itself using the z-score transformation, and then trimming any rows with values less than -3 or greater than 3. This works because z-score transformations rescale the numeric data so that they have means of zero and standard deviations in integer increments.

Here is the implementation of this approach, using 3 standard deviations as our threshold. Note: 3 is an arbitrary selection, and this parameter can be modified. Use your own judgement and domain knowledge to determine an appropriate value.

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats

# Calculate z-scores for the 'Food_Avg' variable
z_scores = stats.zscore(Cgy_DAs['Automobile_Avg'])

# Set the threshold for outliers (use a value that makes sense to you)
threshold = 3

# Trim the outliers
Cgy_DAs_trimmed = Cgy_DAs[(z_scores < threshold) & (z_scores > -threshold)]

Now that we have implemented the trimming operation, let us compare the input and output data frames to get a sense of how many samples were trimmed.

In [ ]:
# Verify the dimensions of the input and output data frames

print("Dimensions of Cgy_DAs_trimmed:", Cgy_DAs_trimmed.shape)

Dimensions of Cgy_DAs: (1559, 12)

Discretizing Target¶

Since we aiming to build a classification model, I need to discretize our target variable. Here, I adopt the qcut method and set the desired quantiles to 3, as I want my target variable to be binned into three categories: Low, Medium, and High.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd

# Create labels for quantiles
labels = ["Low", "Medium", "High"]

# Discretize Food_Avg into four quantiles with equal counts and assign custom labels
Cgy_DAs_binned = Cgy_DAs_trimmed.copy()  # Make a copy to avoid modifying the original
Cgy_DAs_binned['Auto_Avg_Quantiles'] = pd.qcut(Cgy_DAs_trimmed['Automobile_Avg'], q=3, labels=labels)

# Preview the results
print(Cgy_DAs_binned[['Automobile_Avg', 'Auto_Avg_Quantiles']].head())

   Automobile_Avg Auto_Avg_Quantiles
0          641.39             Medium
1          478.62                Low
2          592.58             Medium
3          743.77             Medium
4          560.25                Low

From reviewing the output, I can see that the new variable was successfully added. In addition, it looks like the numeric values associated with the new variables are consistent with the class labels, so I am confident in proceeding.

Re-Scaling the Data¶

The final step in preparation for modelling is to re-scale our data using z-score transformations. This ensures all of numeric predictors on the same scale, which prevents bias in the model building phase.

We will use the StandardScaler module from scikit-learn to scale our data.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Set the scaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Select only the numeric variables

                   'Food_Avg', 'Shelter_Avg', 'Marital_Ratio',
                   'Bachelor_and_Above', 'Healthcare_Avg']

# Transform the selected variables
Cgy_DAs_scaled = Cgy_DAs_select.copy()

Building a Classification Model¶

Using the scikit-learn package, I will build a simple classification model based on a decision tree.

Create Training/Test Splits and Train the Model¶

The following code chunk uses the standard workflow for generating training/test splits of the data (to avoid overfitting), as well as training a simple classification model using the DecisionTreeClassifier from the scikit-learn package.

After loading the appropriate modules, I separate the predictors and target variable, split my data into training/test data (80/20), initialize the classifier, and train the model.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report

# Separate predictors and target variable
X = Cgy_DAs_scaled[['Population', 'Income_Median', 'Age_Median', 
                    'Food_Avg', 'Shelter_Avg', 'Marital_Ratio', 
                    'Bachelor_and_Above', 'Healthcare_Avg']]
y = Cgy_DAs_scaled['Auto_Avg_Quantiles']

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2)

# Initialize and train the model ------ clf is shorthand for classifier
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

Evaluate the Model¶

Now that the model is trained, we can evaluate it's performance. We will use Classification Accuracy and the Confusion Matrix as our primary scoring metrics.

In [ ]:
# Check the model accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, clf.predict(X_test))
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)

Accuracy: 0.6428571428571429

Our model accuracy appears to be okay. Not great, but not terrible either. More data would probably help in this case.

import numpy as np

# Plot confusion matrix as heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False, square=True)

# Add value annotations
for i in range(conf_matrix.shape[0]):
    for j in range(conf_matrix.shape[1]):
        plt.text(j + 0.5, i + 0.5, str(conf_matrix[i, j]), ha='center', va='center', color='black')

# Fix tick labels
tick_labels = ['High', 'Low', 'Medium']
plt.xticks(ticks=np.arange(0.5, len(tick_labels)), labels=tick_labels)
plt.yticks(ticks=np.arange(0.5, len(tick_labels)), labels=tick_labels)

plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('Actual Label')
plt.show()

Note that here I have things ordered High, Low, and Medium. This is because the modelling process has encoded the target variables as numeric by first sorting the categorical data alphabetically.

Summary¶

The model performance is not the best, by any means. However, it was able to predict correctly the majority of the data classification. As expected, the 'High' classification performed the best compared to the other two classes. This can likely be attributed to the positive skew of the dataset therefore, there would have been a more obvious distinction of classification from 'Medium' average spend to 'High' average spend. By the same logic, it makes sense that the model had a more challenging time correctly distunguishing between 'Low' and 'Medium' classes.

Ultimately, a better distribution of data and perhaps better predictor variable selections would result in a more accurate model.
